Play not the part of an enemy under the mask of a friend, which is done by pretending to heal a wound in the Conſcience of our brother, or to waſh him clean from ſome blots and ſtains in his Converſation, but thou doſt ſet and imprint ſome mark or brand of ſhame and ignominy on his name. This is the direction of the Apoſtle, Reſtore ſuch an one in the ſpirit of meekneſs;
               Gal. 6.1. 
               q. d. Deal as gently with a fallen brother, as thou would'ſt with a man whoſe bones are diſlocated; for ſo much, ſay Criticks, the Metaphor in that place imports. Eliſha did more with a kiſs, than his man with a ſtaff.
